<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-14</title>

<p><b>What this run found.</b> The Hugging Face Papers feed was effectively flat for 2026-06-13/14, so I went deep on the strongest papers that surfaced at the end of the previous week. Two threads dominate. First, robot world models are being re-architected for speed and utility: <b>WEAVER</b> shows that a latent flow-matching transformer with learned reward and critic heads can evaluate, improve, and plan on a real Franka, while <b>RepWAM</b> argues that the visual-action tokenizer itself should be representation-centric rather than reconstruction-centric. Second, autonomous research agents are being reframed as an environment-engineering problem: <b>EurekAgent</b> wraps off-the-shelf CLI agents in permission, artifact, budget, and human-in-the-loop scaffolding and reports state-of-the-art results across math, kernel engineering, and ML engineering. In both areas, the most interesting work is moving from "bigger model" to "better interface between model and world."</p>

<h1>Theme 1: Robot world models are becoming fast, latent, and useful</h1>

<p>World models for manipulation have long promised policy evaluation, improvement, and planning without expensive real-world rollouts, but the trifecta of fidelity, long-horizon consistency, and inference speed has been elusive. This week two papers attack the problem from complementary angles: WEAVER by making the whole pipeline efficient enough to close the loop, and RepWAM by redesigning the latent space on which the model is built.</p>

