<h2>WEAVER: a flow-matching world model that closes the loop on real hardware</h2>

<p>Jain et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13672">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13672">PDF</a> · <a href="https://arnavkj1995.github.io/WEAVER/">project</a></p>

<p>WEAVER (World Estimation Across Views for Embodied Reasoning) is the most complete attempt I have seen to make a robot world model practical for all three downstream uses at once: evaluation, policy improvement, and test-time planning. The core bet is that you can get fidelity, long-horizon consistency, and speed by fusing ingredients from video generation (flow matching, diffusion forcing, a pretrained SD3 VAE), latent world models (learned reward and value heads), and manipulation-specific architectures (multi-view memory and history).</p>

<p>The setup is a standard visuomotor policy loop. At each step the robot observes multi-view RGB images <latex>I_t^1, \dots, I_t^n</latex> and proprioception <latex>q_t \in \mathbb{R}^8</latex>; a base policy <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex> proposes an <latex>h</latex>-step action chunk <latex>\mathbf{a}_t</latex>; and the world model imagines the resulting future latents. WEAVER encodes images with a frozen SD3 VAE, concatenates per-view patch tokens with a state token, an action token, and a flow-timestep token, and runs a 32-layer block-causal transformer. Two conditioning windows keep the generation coherent: a sparse long-term memory of every 5th past latent, and a 2-frame short-term history.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:weaver:architecture]]</p>

<p>The training objective is conditional flow matching in v-prediction form, with diffusion forcing applied independently across future timesteps:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="WEAVER flow-matching loss (v-pred)"><code>x1 = z[t+1 : t+h+1]                 # ground-truth future latents
x0 = torch.randn_like(x1)            # Gaussian noise
tau = torch.rand(...)                # one noise level per frame (diffusion forcing)
xt = tau * x1 + (1 - tau) * x0
v = x1 - x0
loss = MSE(v, model(xt, actions, tau, memory, history))</code></pre>

<p>I cloned the official repository and reconstructed the released <code>WEAVER</code> config without downloading the 8.2 GB checkpoint. The parameter count comes out to <b>928,735,746</b> trainable parameters — 98.5% in the dynamics core, only ~1.5% in the latent reward and critic heads. This matches the paper's claimed 928 M almost exactly and is a good sanity check that the public config is the one used for the reported numbers.</p>

<p>For inference, WEAVER uses a pyramid noise schedule so earlier future frames become clean context for later frames, plus KV caching over the constant memory/history tokens and, critically, a ReFlow distillation stage that brings NFE down from 23 to 4. The speedup is structural: the same backbone can be run at very different latency points. That is what makes the reported 5–10× speedup over Ctrl-World mechanically plausible even though I could not measure wall-clock time without a GPU.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="140"/><col width="100"/><col width="100"/><col width="100"/><col width="100"/><col width="100"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Method</th><th background-color="light-gray">NFE</th><th background-color="light-gray">ext. FID↓</th><th background-color="light-gray">ext. FVD↓</th><th background-color="light-gray">wrist FVD↓</th><th background-color="light-gray">time (s)↓</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Ctrl-World</td><td>16</td><td>26.09</td><td>78.73</td><td>195.37</td><td>14.65</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Ctrl-World</td><td>50</td><td>22.44</td><td>55.05</td><td>91.77</td><td>42.33</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>WEAVER</b></td><td>16</td><td><b>10.20</b></td><td><b>27.83</b></td><td><b>90.72</b></td><td><b>4.78</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>WEAVER</b></td><td>50</td><td><b>9.51</b></td><td><b>26.54</b></td><td><b>66.89</b></td><td><b>14.25</b></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The downstream results are striking. For policy evaluation, WEAVER-FT reaches a Pearson correlation of <latex>\rho = 0.87</latex> with real-world success rate. For policy improvement, fine-tuning <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex> on synthetic data filtered by predicted advantage matches fine-tuning on real data within 4% and improves over the base policy by 38%. For test-time planning, best-of-N sampling with the latent verifier improves success by 14% with a latency budget that Ctrl-World cannot meet.</p>

<p>What makes the planning result work is the latent verifier. Instead of decoding every imagined frame and querying an external VLM judge, WEAVER trains lightweight reward and critic heads directly on imagined latents. The advantage for a candidate action chunk is</p>

<p><latex>\hat{A}_t = \sum_{\ell=1}^{H} \gamma^{\ell-1} R(\hat{z}_{t+\ell}, \ell) + \gamma^H V(\hat{z}_{t+H}, \ell) - V(z_t, \ell).</latex></p>

<p>This is standard RL machinery, but operating on imagined latents rather than rendered pixels is what makes sub-second planning possible. The main caveat is that I could not download the checkpoints or run on real DROID data, so the FID/FVD and real-robot numbers remain the authors' claims, even though the architecture and scale are code-verified.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>RepWAM: representation-centric tokenization for world-action models</h2>

<p>Wang et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13674">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13674">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/wdrink/RepWAM">code (placeholder)</a></p>

<p>RepWAM asks a more foundational question: what kind of latent space should a world-action model live in? Current WAMs typically inherit visual tokenizers from pretrained video generators, which are optimized for pixel reconstruction, not for manipulation semantics. RepWAM instead trains a <b>representation visual-action tokenizer</b> (RepViTok) that aligns visual latents with a frozen visual foundation model and learns latent actions as transitions in the same semantic space.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:repwam:tokenizer]]</p>

<p>The tokenizer has two parts. The visual tokenizer is a ViT autoencoder trained with reconstruction, perceptual, GAN, and semantic-alignment losses:</p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L}_{\text{vis}} = \lambda_1 \|o - \hat{o}\|_1 + \lambda_{\text{perc}} \mathcal{L}_{\text{perc}} + \lambda_{\text{gan}} \mathcal{L}_{\text{gan}} + \lambda_{\text{align}} \| \text{avg}(W_{\text{align}} z) - \text{avg}(G(o)) \|_2^2.</latex></p>

<p>On top of the frozen visual latents, a Latent Action Tokenizer (LAT) couples an inverse dynamics model <latex>q_\phi</latex> with a forward dynamics model <latex>f_\psi</latex>:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="RepWAM latent action tokenizer"><code>l_t = idm(z_t, z_t+1)                          # latent action, d_l = 4
K_t, delta_t = fdm(z_t, l_t)                   # transport + residual
z_hat_t+1 = K_t @ z_t + delta_t                # next latent prediction</code></pre>

<p><latex>K_t \in \mathbb{R}^{L \times L}</latex> is a soft transport matrix over spatial tokens, inspired by optical flow in token space; <latex>\delta_t</latex> captures non-transportable changes. The LAT is trained with forward next-latent prediction plus backward consistency on reversed pairs.</p>

<p>The causal WAM itself is a diffusion transformer over visual-action chunks. Each chunk interleaves visual tokens and latent-action tokens; a block-causal mask lets each chunk attend only to language conditioning, the initial visual context, and previous chunks. The model is pretrained on video + latent-action tokens from AgiBot (~100 G tokens), then adapted to real robot actions from AgiBot, RoboMIND, RoboCOIN, and InternAI (~300 G tokens).</p>

<p>The official repository is currently a placeholder, so I could not trace the full implementation. Instead I built a minimal CPU-runnable probe of the core equations on synthetic moving-blob videos. The probe confirms that the LAT objective trains stably (held-out forward MSE &lt; 1e-4) and that the causal WAM flow-matching loss falls from ~2.3 to ~0.15 over 15 epochs. That validates the math, but it says nothing about manipulation semantics or the reported RoboTwin 2.0 numbers.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="160"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Tokenizer</th><th background-color="light-gray">gFVD↓ seen</th><th background-color="light-gray">PSNR↑ seen</th><th background-color="light-gray">OLS↑ seen</th><th background-color="light-gray">gFVD↓ unseen</th><th background-color="light-gray">PickFruit↑</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>WAN2.2 VAE</td><td>67.42</td><td>17.34</td><td>13.68</td><td>83.98</td><td>20%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ViTok</td><td>69.23</td><td>17.21</td><td>16.29</td><td>80.14</td><td>10%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>RepViTok</b></td><td><b>61.01</b></td><td><b>18.47</b></td><td><b>18.82</b></td><td><b>72.91</b></td><td><b>30%</b></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The ablation above is from the paper and should be read with the code-unavailable caveat. The interesting structural point is that RepWAM explicitly decouples <i>semantic visual dynamics</i> from <i>embodiment-specific motor commands</i> through an intermediate latent-action stage, whereas contemporaries like Lingbot-VA model real robot actions directly inside a pretrained WAN2.2 VAE. Whether the reported gains come from the tokenizer design or from the extra pretraining stage is a question only the released code and weights can settle.</p>

<h1>Theme 2: Autonomous research as environment engineering</h1>

<p>Autonomous scientific discovery has been dominated by prescribed workflows: evolutionary search, solution trees, test-time RL. EurekAgent turns the lens outward and asks whether the bottleneck is now the environment rather than the agent algorithm.</p>

