<h2>EurekAgent: building the sandbox, not just the agent</h2>

<p>Xin et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13662">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13662">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/THU-Team-Eureka/EurekAgent">code</a></p>

<p>EurekAgent's central claim is that the bottleneck for autonomous scientific discovery is shifting from prescribing agent workflows to designing agent environments. The system wraps off-the-shelf CLI agents in four environment-engineering dimensions: permissions, artifacts, budget, and human-in-the-loop oversight. Within those boundaries the agents are free to choose their own search strategy.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:eurekagent:overview]]</p>

<p>The outer loop is intentionally minimal:</p>

<pre lang="text" caption="EurekAgent stage loop"><code>prepare → [ propose → { implement }_p=1..P ]_r=1..R</code></pre>

<ul>
  <li><b>Prepare</b> validates the problem, tests the grader, installs dependencies, and writes a stage-gate artifact.</li>
  <li><b>Propose</b> launches one agent session that distills prior rounds and the web into a manifest of up to <latex>P</latex> hypotheses.</li>
  <li><b>Implement</b> runs up to <latex>P</latex> parallel agent sessions, each confined to its own workspace, submitting candidates to a secure grader.</li>
</ul>

<p>The environment layer is where the work lives. Permissions engineering uses Docker isolation, a hidden grader container, GPU locks, and a PreToolUse hook that blocks writes to controller-owned result files and same-round peer access. Artifact engineering uses the filesystem plus Git history as shared memory: preparation summaries, hypothesis manifests, ranked solution histories, and evaluator feedback all persist across sessions. Budget engineering tracks wall-clock time per stage and API cost across sessions, with resume support if a run is interrupted.</p>

<p>I cloned the official implementation and ran two probes. The first starts the official FastAPI grader for the circle-packing task, submits a valid candidate, and verifies that the server writes <code>best_result.jsonl</code> and <code>intermediate_results.jsonl</code> while rejecting an invalid submission. The second exercises the <code>TokenTracker</code> cost accounting. Both mechanisms work as documented, which means the environment-engineering design is implemented, not just conceptual.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="160"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Task</th><th background-color="light-gray">EurekAgent</th><th background-color="light-gray">Prev. best AI</th><th background-color="light-gray">Prev. best human</th><th background-color="light-gray">Cost</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>26-circle packing (↑)</td><td><b>2.635999</b></td><td>2.635986</td><td>~2.634</td><td>~$11</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Erdős min. overlap (↓)</td><td><b>0.380870</b></td><td>0.380876</td><td>0.380927</td><td>part of &lt;$17</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1st autocorr. ineq. (↓)</td><td><b>1.502861</b></td><td>1.502863</td><td>1.509730</td><td>part of &lt;$17</td></tr>
    <tr><td>TriMul kernel (↓)</td><td><b>2005 µs</b></td><td>2248 µs</td><td>2096 µs</td><td>A100 time</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The reported results are strong: new AI records on all three math tasks, a new best on the TriMul kernel engineering task, and 85.71% any-medal rate on a seven-task MLE-Bench Lite subset. The authors achieve this with GLM-5.1, an open model, at an average API cost below $17 for the math suite. That is a meaningful efficiency signal if it holds up.</p>

<p>The key caveat is that I did not run the full autonomous loop. Reproducing the $11 circle-packing result would require ~9 hours of agent time with Claude Code/GLM-5.1 plus API credits, and the TriMul/MLE-Bench results need GPUs and held-out data. The probes validate the environment mechanisms; the SOTA numbers should be reported as the authors' results.</p>

<p>Comparing EurekAgent with its neighbors sharpens the point. AlphaEvolve prescribes an evolutionary loop; AIDE prescribes a solution-tree agent; TTT-Discover uses test-time RL that updates model weights per problem. EurekAgent prescribes almost none of that. It gives general-purpose CLI agents a bounded, observable, accountable environment and lets them search. That is a genuine design shift, and the code makes it concrete.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations: the interface layer is where the action is</h1>

<p>Two superficially different fields — robot world models and autonomous research agents — are converging on the same insight. The model is no longer the only thing that matters; the interface between the model and the world is becoming the decisive research object.</p>

<p>In robotics, WEAVER's speed comes from re-engineering the inference interface (flow matching, diffusion forcing, ReFlow, latent verifiers). RepWAM's bet is that the tokenizer — the interface between pixels and the model's latent world — should be semantic and action-aligned rather than reconstruction-oriented. In agentic research, EurekAgent's bet is that the environment — the interface between the LLM and the task — should enforce permissions, persist artifacts, bound budgets, and keep humans in the loop. In both cases the model is treated as a powerful but opaque node; the surrounding architecture does the work that makes the node reliable.</p>

<p>One open question ties the two threads together. If world models become fast and faithful enough to serve as simulators for agent actions, and autonomous research agents become environment-engineered enough to explore reliably, then the next interesting systems may be agents that use learned world models as their environment — not to replace real-world experiments, but to make the search for policies and hypotheses far cheaper. Neither paper quite gets there, but both are building the pieces.</p>

<callout emoji="⚠️" background-color="light-yellow" border-color="yellow">
  <p><b>Coverage note:</b> Hugging Face Papers returned empty date-specific lists for 2026-06-13 and 2026-06-14. This run therefore treats 2026-06-08 to 2026-06-12 as the effective recent pool and deep-dives the strongest papers from that window not already covered in <code>runs/INDEX.md</code>.</p>
</callout>
